1 electricity; including management of onsite sewage disposal systems;
2 (s) Licensing or franchising of cable television;
3 (t) Provision of streets and roads, bridges, tunnels and related facilities,
4 elimination of grade crossings, provision of parking facilities, and
5 enforcement of traffic and parking regulations;
6 (u) Provision of police and fire protection;
7 (v) Regulation of taxis, buses, and other passenger vehicles for hire;
8 (w) Provision and operation of air, rail and bus terminals, port facilities, and
9 public transportation systems;
10 (x) Promotion of economic development of the county, directly or in cooperation
11 with public or private agencies, including the provision of access roads, land
12 and buildings, and promotion of tourism and conventions;
13 (y) Care and maintenance of pedestrian swinging bridges that are available for
14 recreation and public enjoyment;
15 (z) Preservation of historic structures; and
16 (aa)[(z)] Regulation of establishments or commercial enterprises offering adult
17 entertainment and adult entertainment activities.
18 (4) The county judge/executive is hereby authorized and empowered to exercise all[ of]
19 the executive powers pursuant to this section.
20 (5) A county acting under authority of this section may assume, own, possess, and
21 control assets, rights, and liabilities related to the functions and services of the
22 county.
23 (6) (a) If a county is authorized to regulate an area which the Commonwealth[state]
24 also regulates, the county government may regulate the area only by enacting
25 ordinances which are consistent with state law or administrative regulation.[:]
26 (b)[(a)] If the state statute or administrative regulation prescribes a single
27 standard of conduct, a county ordinance is consistent if it is identical to the
Page 3 of 7
