UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2367
1 state statute or administrative regulation.[;]
2 (c)[(b)] If the state statute or administrative regulation prescribes a minimal
3 standard of conduct, a county ordinance is consistent if it establishes a
4 standard which is the same as or more stringent than the state standard.[;]
5 (d)[(c)] A county government may adopt ordinances which incorporate by
6 reference state statutes and administrative regulations in areas in which a
7 county government is authorized to act.
8 (7) County ordinances which prescribe penalties for their violation shall be enforced
9 throughout the entire area of the county unless:
10 (a) Otherwise provided by statute; or
11 (b) The legislative body of any city within the county has adopted an ordinance
12 pertaining to the same subject matter which is the same as or more stringent
13 than the standards that are set forth in the county ordinance. The fiscal court
14 shall forward a copy of each ordinance which is to be enforced throughout the
15 entire area of the county to the mayor of each city in the county.
16 (8) (a) The powers granted to counties by this section shall be in addition to all other
17 powers granted to counties by other provisions of law. These powers, other
18 than the power to tax, may be exercised cooperatively by:
19 1. Two (2) or more counties;[, or by ]
20 2. A county and a city;[, or by ]
21 3. A county and a special district;[,] or[ by ]
22 4. A county and the Commonwealth[state] through, but not limited to,
23 joint contracts, joint ownership of property, or the exchange of services,
24 including personnel and equipment.
25 When counties cooperate in the provision of public services, contracts shall be
26 drawn to document the benefits and relative cost for each of the participating
27 governments. One (1) government may pay one hundred percent (100%), or a
