1 lesser percentage, of all or any part of the cost of the joint undertaking, based
2 upon the written contract required by this subsection.
3 (b) A permissive procedure authorized by this section shall not be deemed to be
4 exclusive or to prohibit the exercise of other existing laws and laws which
5 may hereafter be enacted but shall be an alternative or supplement thereto.
6 (9) Any agency of county government exercising authority pursuant to subsection
7 (3)(z)[(y)] of this section shall, prior to exercising the[such] authority, obtain the
8 voluntary written consent of the owner of the structure. Consent may be obtained
9 only after advising the owner in writing of any advantages and disadvantages to the
10 owner which are likely to result from the exercise of the[such] authority.
11 Section 2. KRS 411.190 is amended to read as follows:
12 (1) As used in this section:
13 (a) "Land" means land, rocks, boulders, cliffs, roads, water, watercourses,
14 pedestrian swinging bridges, private ways and buildings, structures, and
15 machinery or equipment when attached to the realty;
16 (b) "Owner" means the possessor of a fee, reversionary, or easement interest, a
17 tenant, lessee, occupant, local government that expends public funds to
18 maintain pedestrian swinging bridges that are available for recreation and
19 public enjoyment, or person in control of the premises;
20 (c) "Recreational purpose" includes[,] but is not limited to[,] any of the following,
21 or any combination thereof: hunting, fishing, swimming, boating, camping,
22 picnicking, hiking, rock climbing, bouldering, rappelling, bicycling,
23 horseback riding, pleasure driving, nature study, water-skiing, winter sports,
24 and viewing or enjoying historical, archaeological, scenic, or scientific sites;
25 and
26 (d) "Charge" means the admission price or fee asked in return for invitation or
27 permission to enter or go upon the land but does not include fees for general
Page 5 of 7
XXXX 2/26/2026 9:28 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2367
1 use permits issued by a government agency for access to public lands if the
2 permits are valid for a period of not less than thirty (30) days.
3 (2) The purpose of this section is to encourage owners of land to make land and water
4 areas available to the public for recreational purposes by limiting their liability
5 toward persons entering thereon for such purposes.
6 (3) Except as specifically recognized by or provided in subsection (6) of this section, an
7 owner of land owes no duty of care to keep the premises safe for entry or use by
8 others for recreational purposes, or to give any warning of a dangerous condition,
9 use, structure, or activity on the premises to persons entering for such purposes.
10 (4) Except as specifically recognized by or provided in subsection (6) of this section, an
11 owner of land who either directly or indirectly invites or permits without charge any
12 person to use the property for recreation purposes does not thereby:
13 (a) Extend any assurance that the premises are safe for any purpose;
14 (b) Confer upon the person the legal status of an invitee or licensee to whom a
15 duty of care is owed; or
16 (c) Assume responsibility for or incur liability for any injury to person or
17 property caused by an act or omission of those persons.
18 (5) Unless otherwise agreed in writing, the provisions of subsections (3) and (4) of this
19 section shall be deemed applicable to the duties and liability of an owner of land
20 leased to:
21 (a) The state or any subdivision thereof for recreational purposes; and
22 (b) A local government that maintains one (1) or more pedestrian swinging
23 bridges that are available for recreation and public enjoyment on the land.
24 (6) [Nothing in ]This section shall not limit[limits] in any way any liability that[which]
25 otherwise exists:
26 (a) For willful or malicious failure to guard or warn against a dangerous
27 condition, use, structure, or activity; or
Page 6 of 7
XXXX 2/26/2026 9:28 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2367
1 (b) For injury suffered in any case where the owner of land charges the person or
2 persons who enter or go on the land for the recreational use thereof, except
3 that in the case of land leased to the state or a subdivision thereof, any
4 consideration received by the owner for the lease shall not be deemed a
5 charge within the meaning of this section.
6 (7) [Nothing in ]This section shall not be construed to:
7 (a) Create a duty of care, a duty of protection from danger or risk to any
8 individual or the public in general, or other ground of liability for injury to
9 persons or property;
10 (b) Relieve any person using the land of another for recreational purposes from
11 any obligation which he or she may have in the absence of this section to
12 exercise care in his or her use of the land and in his or her activities thereon,
13 or from the legal consequences of failure to employ such care; or
14 (c) Ripen into a claim for adverse possession[,] absent a claim of title or legal
15 right.
16 (8) An[No] action for the recovery of real property, including establishment of
17 prescriptive easement, right-of-way, or adverse possession, shall not[may] be
18 brought by any person whose claim is based on use solely for recreational purposes.
